@saper There are various reasons we have data that is non-public. Our lending library is an example, as ethus3h points out.

Uploading non-public data requires uploading to an access-restricted collection. You'll need to contact info@archive.org to get this setup if you need it for some reason. For obvious reasons, we only do this when necessary (e.g. if something can only be archived if it's not made public at the moment). It's not something we encourage, but an access control tool we use when necessary.

info@archive.org can also answer any other questions you have about this.

@cablehead I am guessing the root cause here is that `asyncio` was already installed in the python2 environment and the [setup.py check](https://github.com/cablehead/python-consul/blob/master/setup.py#L26-L34) skips the deletion of `aio.py` module. The `aio.py` module will not work with python2 and hence will fail if imported.

We need to do one of the following;
1. add a conditional logic to wrap the whole module
2. improve the check in `setup.py` to remove if PY3
3. move the aio module to a new project `python-consul-aio`

Thoughts?

