The problem isn't an inheritance one, but rather it appears to be a problem with `def_static`s of the same name across inheritance trees.  I changed your example to this:

```C++
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <iostream>

class MyBase {
public:
    static std::unique_ptr<MyBase> make() {
        std::cerr << "MyBase::make()" << std::endl;
        return std::unique_ptr<MyBase>(new MyBase());
    }
    virtual ~MyBase() = default;
};

class MyDerived : public MyBase {
public:
    static std::unique_ptr<MyDerived> make() {
        std::cerr << "MyDerived::make()" << std::endl;
        return std::unique_ptr<MyDerived>(new MyDerived());
    }
};


PYBIND11_PLUGIN(issue511) {
    namespace py = pybind11;
    py::module m("issue511", "Issue 511 test");

    py::class_<MyBase>(m, "MyBase")
        .def_static("make", &MyBase::make);

    py::class_<MyDerived>(m, "MyDerived", py::base<MyBase>())
        .def_static("make", &MyDerived::make)
        .def_static("make2", &MyDerived::make)
        ;

    return m.ptr();
};
```

with Python:
```Python
from issue511 import MyBase, MyDerived

b = MyBase.make()
d1 = MyDerived.make2()
d2 = MyDerived.make()

assert isinstance(b, MyBase)
assert isinstance(d1, MyDerived)
assert isinstance(d2, MyDerived)
```

When I compile that and run it, I get:

```
MyBase::make()
MyDerived::make()
MyBase::make()
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "test.py", line 9, in <module>
    assert isinstance(d2, MyDerived)
AssertionError
```

Notice the `d1 = ...` is going to the right place (MyDerived), but the `d2 = ...` isn't: it ends up calling `MyBase::make()`.  So the actual inheritance (and recognition of subobjects) is working fine.  The bug, rather, is in how the static method gets set up.  (Suggest re-titling this to something like "static methods on derived classes are ignored in favour of base class static methods with the same name".)

@gilou's PR #3394 stores renew hooks in renewal conf files, which I think is correct, and addresses the most central core of this problem, so we have a pr for part of this.

But I think @bmw talked offline about what happens when the user had five different lineages, each with different renew hooks, and then supplies another renew hook on the command line.  As #3394 is written, the one on the command line will replace all the others. We might instead want to accumulate hooks from renewal conf files and the command line and run them all? Although that would create horrible special cases in the way renewal conf files are managed...

We may also still need some handling for pre- and post- hooks.

